The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut — — Looking back, it's usually the case that financial crises seem to have warning signs; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
The situation in Lebanon is no different now, with an anticipated crisis having plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975–1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, external capital inflows had to stop. This turning point came in late 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
The sudden stop of this capital has brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit is as high as 25 percent of GDP, and its export base is too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals over 150 percent of GDP.
The government's revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic decline, with the budget deficit already significant at 10% of GDP in 2019 and still rapidly expanding.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Major banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have heavily invested in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their portfolios), and are now basically insolvent.
These crises have pushed the Lebanese economy into a deep crisis.
Companies eager to borrow and import have started laying off workers or closing down completely.
Economic decline could potentially lead to a depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil, but rather the diaspora, who are attracted to invest due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
So it is not surprising to see signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: savings have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an unlikely level — just 3% of GDP.
Inequality is very high and continues to rise.
The real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50% between 2000 and 2015, greatly weakening the tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated youth.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites siphoned off wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage-based ruling group.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges remain completely unresolved.
A financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular movement of revolution took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has responded to Lebanon's economic problems overwhelmingly in favor of the elite, indicating that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, and further consolidate sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the major shareholders of each bank, including ruling politicians, to decide how to quantitatively withdraw cash.
In reality, this enables elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens find it difficult to access their deposits.
In addition, the central bank lowered deposit rates but has not lowered public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its major foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may begin to sell state-owned assets at fire-sale prices to elite-connected entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while elites are allowed to obtain low-exchange-rate dollars, whereas ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly depreciating market exchange rate. The current market exchange rate is discounted by 40%.
When the country starts printing lira to pay public sector wages, depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been using lira to pay interest on dollar deposits (which account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to eliminate public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction is passed on to depositors through the "dollarization" of deposits held by depositors, the banks' equity is basically safe.
If this situation becomes reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions and the liquidation of savings.
The migration process of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the diaspora community — — which the system relies on — — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system, which can be controlled by increasingly inexpensive patronage.
In the end, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
By contrast, the revolutionaries' push for the establishment of a new republic will take a completely different approach.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, patronage, and inequality.
They hope to build a dynamic high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural power house, and create more synergies with the diaspora community.
In order to achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank equity, and forcibly reduce deposits of 1% depositors who account for more than 50% of total deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the inevitable recession alleviated by support from the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
The infighting over the composition of the next Lebanese government is part of a larger struggle in the country's quest for a new political solution.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains uncertain.
